      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "9747e951",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "9747e951"
      },
      "source": [
        "Unlike strings, lists are mutable. When the bracket operator appears on\n",
        "the left side of an assignment, it identifies the element of the list\n",
        "that will be assigned."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "98ec5d9c",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "98ec5d9c"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "5097a517",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "5097a517"
      },
      "source": [
        "The second element of `numbers`, which used to be `123`, is now `17`.\n",
        "\n",
        "List indices work the same way as string indices:\n",
        "\n",
        "-   Any integer expression can be used as an index.\n",
        "\n",
        "-   If you try to read or write an element that does not exist, you get\n",
        "    an `IndexError`.\n",
        "\n",
        "-   If an index has a negative value, it counts backward from the end of\n",
        "    the list.\n",
        "\n",
        "The `in` operator works on lists -- it checks whether a given element appears anywhere in the list."
      ]
    },
